<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 4.9, Applications to Markov Chains</title>

  <!-- Stopping point as of Feb 20.-->

  <ul marker="">

    <!-- Problem 1 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; Determine whether <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are regular stochastic matrices.</p>

      <p>
        <me>
        P =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          0.8 &amp; 0 \\
          0.2 &amp; 1
        \end{pmatrix},
        \qquad
        Q = \tfrac{1}{4}
        \begin{pmatrix}
          1 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 \\
          0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\
          3 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
        \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 2 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; Consider the Markov chain below.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-tikz-markov">
        <caption>A figure of a Markov chain. </caption>
            <image width="40%" xml:id="markov">
            <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture} [node distance=5mm]<!-- [>=Stealth, node distance=34mm, thick] -->
        \tikzstyle{state}=[circle, draw, minimum size=18pt, inner sep=0pt]
        % Nodes at triangle vertices
        \node[state] (A) at (0,0) {A};
        \node[state] (B) at (3, 2) {B};
        \node[state] (C) at (4, 0) {C};

        % Edges with probabilities
        \path[->]
            (A) edge[loop left] node[midway, above left]{\small $\tfrac{1}{2}$} (A)
            (A) edge[] node[midway, above right]{\small $\tfrac{1}{2}$} (B)
            (B) edge[loop right] node[midway, below left]{\small $\tfrac{1}{2}$} (B)
            (B) edge[] node[midway, below right]{\small $\tfrac{1}{2}$} (C)
            (C) edge[loop right] node[midway, above left]{\small $\tfrac{3}{4}$} (C)
            (C) edge[] node[midway, right]{\small $\tfrac{1}{4}$} (A);
        \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

      <p>What is the transition matrix? Calculate the steady‑state vector.</p>
    </li>
    
    </ul>
    <ul marker = "">

    <!-- Problem 3 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; Suppose there are two cities, X and Y. Every year:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><p>70% of the people from X stay in X, the remaining 30% move to Y.</p></li>
        <li><p>40% of the people from Y stay in Y, the remaining 60% move to X.</p></li>
      </ul>

      <p>The initial populations of X and Y are 100 and 200, respectively.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>What is the stochastic matrix that represents this situation?</p></li>
        <li><p>After a long period of time, what is the population in city X?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 4 -->
    <li workspace="1in">
      <p>(4) &#160; <em>Written Explanation Exercise</em>  
      Let <m>P</m> be a stochastic <m>n \times n</m> matrix with positive entries.  
      Give two methods of finding the steady‑state solution.</p>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 5 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(5) &#160; A mouse lives in a maze that has at least three rooms.  
      Each room is connected to at least one other room (in other words, every room is connected).  
      Every hour the mouse moves to a connected room with equal probability.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>Design any mouse maze and its corresponding transition matrix <m>P</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Is your <m>P</m> regular stochastic?</p></li>
        <li><p>In the long run, is there a room the mouse is more likely to be in? If so, which one?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    
    <p><i>Note: this problem is related to the PageRank problem that we explore later in this class.</i></p>

  </ul>
</handout>